04983nam a22009615i 9780520912380DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209123807 a10.1525/97805209123802doi  a(DE-B1597)544153  a(OCoLC)1149441277  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHX947.Z67bO76413 1992 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a335/.83/092aB2201 aOsugi, Sakae, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Autobiography of Osugi Sakae /cSakae Osugi.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVoices from Asia ;v600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tTRANSLATOR'S INTRODUCTION -- tCHRONOLOGY OF MAJOR EVENTS IN THE AUTOBIOGRAPHY -- tTHE AUTOBIOGRAPHY OF ÖSUGI SAKAE -- tCHAPTER I. FIRST MEMORIES TO 1894 -- tCHAPTER 2. CHILDHOOD 1894-1895 -- tCHAPTER 3. A YOUNG HOOLIGAN 1895-1899 -- tCHAPTER 4. CADET SCHOOL 1899-1901 -- tCHAPTER 5. A NEW LIFE 1901-1902 -- tCHAPTER 6. MEMORIES OF MOTHER 1902-1904 -- tCHAPTER 7. LIFE IN PRISON 1906-1910 -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Japanese labor movement of the early twentieth century, no one captured the public imagination as vividly as Osugi Sakae (1885-1923): rebel, anarchist, and martyr. Flamboyant in life, dramatic in death, Osugi came to be seen as a romantic hero fighting the oppressiveness of family and society.Osugi helped to create this public persona when he published his autobiography (Jijoden) in 1921-22. Now available in English for the first time, this work offers a rare glimpse into a Japanese boy's life at the time of the Sino-Japanese (1894-95) and the Russo-Japanese (1904-5) wars. It reveals the innocent—and not-so-innocent—escapades of children in a provincial garrison town and the brutalizing effects of discipline in military preparatory schools. Subsequent chapters follow Osugi to Tokyo, where he discovers the excitement of radical thought and politics.Byron Marshall rounds out this picture of the early Osugi with a translation of his Prison Memoirs (Gokuchuki), originally published in 1919. This essay, one of the world's great pieces of prison writing, describes in precise detail the daily lives of Japanese prisoners, especially those incarcerated for political crimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnarchistszJapanvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a20th century japanese history.  a20th century japanese political movements.  aamakasu incident.  aanarchism.  aanarchist periodicals.  aanarchist.  aautobiography.  adiscipline.  aesperanto school.  agarrison town.  ajapan.  ajapanese labor movement.  ajapanese prisoners.  ajapanese.  alabor.  amartyr.  amilitary school.  aoppression.  aosugi sakae.  apolitical crimes.  apreparatory school.  aprison memoirs.  aprison writing.  apublic persona.  aradical politics.  aradical thought.  aradical.  arebel.  arusso japanese war.  asino japanese war.  atokyo.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007760740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091238040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520912380423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520912380/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  